            <article data-uuid="3ef9eda214b64fb3a13c6a27eadac639">
                <h4 data-uuid="480ca9d94079469496fb3fdcc0d6056f">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="945e9b3897da4cccb9381dab4d6216f5">Labor strikes often turned violent and failed to accomplish their goals.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="22e766263658479b851ff6afb8d87af6">Labor Strikes</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="ded5f51453334e7689d474c5c80cef68"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="040be0a9968340099b16914d44b74f02">By the late 1800s other unions were gaining strength. Major workers’ strikes swept the country and included miners in Colorado, steelworkers in Pennsylvania, and railroad workers in Illinois and California. Some strikes involved violent clashes with police. One of the worst confrontations occurred in Chicago in 1886.</p>
